&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Putin awarded the title of Hero of Russia to the deceased priest.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On May 30, Russian President Vladimir Putin &lt;a href=&quot;http://publication.pravo.gov.ru/document/0001202506030004&quot;&gt;signed&lt;/a&gt; a decree posthumously awarding the title of Hero of Russia to the cleric of the Pskov Diocese, the assistant commander for work with believing military personnel of the 2nd separate special forces brigade of the Leningrad Military District, Priest Antoniy Savchenko &quot;for courage and heroism shown in the performance of civic duty&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Savchenko died on May 12 from a HIMARS strike. Possibly, he was &lt;a href=&quot;https://t.me/shaltnotkill/10080&quot;&gt;at the moment of the missile strike&lt;/a&gt; together with Russian soldiers in a hotel in Rylsk (Kursk region). According to &lt;a href=&quot;https://tass.ru/obschestvo/23975201&quot;&gt;Metropolitan Tikhon Shevkunov&lt;/a&gt;, &quot;our father Antoniy covered the wounded officer with his whole huge strong body. The entire projectile fell on him. But all five, including this officer, were saved.&quot; However, HIMARS is a multiple rocket launcher system, and the priest&#x27;s body is unlikely to have been able to absorb the entire projectile.&lt;/p&gt;

